<TITLE> HK shares track Shanghai slide to hit 4-wk lows </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HONG KONG, May 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Hong Kong stocks fell 1 percent on Wednesday as a slide in mainland equity markets after Beijing hiked the stock trading tax prompted a broad sell-off, with mainland financials leading the decline. Hong Kong-listed shares in mainland companies, or H shares, closed the morning down 2.6 percent. Chinese book publisher and retailer Sichuan Xinhua Winshare Chainstore made a disappointing debut, falling 7 percent after pricing its US$275 million IPO at the top of a range. The overall mood was cautious, but there were no signs of panic selling. "The market is orderly," said Ernie Hon, strategist at ICEA. "We'll have more downside after today. Even if A shares rebound, they will go down again." Hon said concerns that Beijing would take more measures to cool the market would resurface and weigh on shares. China's main stock index had dropped 6.4 percent by 0512 GMT after Beijing raised the stamp tax to 0.3 percent from 0.1 percent in a bid to to cool a speculative market. The benchmark Hang Seng Index had fallen 209.42 points to 20,260.17 by lunch, having earlier tapped its lowest levels since April 30. The China Enterprises Index of H shares dropped 274.10 points, earlier hitting its lowest point since May 4. Turnover was high at HK$44.7 billion (US$5.7 billion), up from Tuesday morning's HK$30.6 billion. Mainland financial stocks were the biggest drag on the H shares. Shares in China Life, the morning's most active, slid 3.7 percent to HK$23.60. Rival Ping An tumbled 3.3 percent to HK$43.45. China Construction Bank slumped 2.4 percent to HK$4.57. Luks Industrial (Group) Ltd. dived 6.3 percent to HK$13.48 after major shareholders sold 70.5 million shares at HK$12.80 each, raising HK$902.4 million (US$115.7 million), according to a term sheet obtained by Reuters on Wednesday. CNOOC Ltd was among the top losers in the resource sector, dropping 3 percent to HK$7.1. PetroChina Co Ltd declined 2 percent to HK$9.88. Investors booked pr